<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Is the data cable by any high current cables or any motors?</strong> - If so it could be EMI (Electromagnetic Interference), as Neopixels can act as gigantic antenna and easily pick up disturbances given the right environment.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>How is it being powered?</strong> You preferably want Neopixel power not running under the Rio bus and on its own <span class="abbreviation">VRM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Voltage Regulator Module"></template></span>. I’ve tried in the past just for testing and had some flickering and disturbances. Make sure you are giving them a clean 5 volts.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Some Neopixel strips (especially the poor quality ones) will not like running at a high refresh rate as well, so maybe try using WPILib’s <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/Notifier.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Notifier</a> instead of publishing the buffer in periodic, but considering it worked on another Rio I would first look at the first two and progress from there.</p>
<p>Hope that helps</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2024-04-01T04:38:24.780Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":176,"readers_count":175,"score":40.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":460852,"topic_slug":"addressable-leds-questions","display_username":"Owen Shaule","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/Notifier.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Notifier (WPILib API 2024.3.2)","clicks":3}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":59310,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Systems Mentor at 10554"},"post_url":"/t/addressable-leds-questions/460852/2","custom_user_title":"Systems Mentor at 10554","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3348900,"name":"Bodi","username":"IthcyPrince","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/i/dc4da7/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-04-01T05:58:36.079Z","cooked":"<p>The code looks correct for the LED’s, and anything wrong in that code should make the entire strip act up, not just individual pixels. I suspect it is something in the way you are setting up your power or signal to the strips (or possibly the strips themselves), but without more information I am unable to make any inferences about what could be causing your issue.</p>","post